qas.question: What did some software do to the ASCII characters?
What interpretation became common in Unix systmes?

answers.text: interpreted DEL as an input character as meaning "remove previously-typed input character"

qas.question: What do most other systmes use the DEL to mean?

answers.text: remove the character at the cursor

qas.question: What did the first systems use DEL to mean?

context: Some software <a0_0><b4_0>assigned special meanings<b4_0/><a0_0/> to ASCII characters sent to the software from the terminal. Operating systems from Digital Equipment Corporation, for example, <a1_0><b5_0>interpreted DEL as an input character as meaning "remove previously-typed input character<b5_0/>"<a1_0/>, and this interpretation also became common in Unix systems. Most other systems used <a3_0><b6_0>BS<b6_0/><a3_0/> for that meaning and used DEL to mean "<a2_0><b7_0>remove the character at the cursor<b7_0/><a2_0/>".[citation needed] That latter interpretation is the most common now.[citation needed]
